\begin_layout Standard
The singularities in the reduced dynamics play a crucial role in the loss of controlled invariance of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 For a trajectory 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 of a general mechanical system
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(1) the vanishing of the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(\theta_{*}\left(t_{s}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 in corresponding reduced dynamics along a parametrization 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{*}\left(t\right)=\phi\left(\theta_{*}\left(t\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 imposes a specific constraint on the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 under the assumption that namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{*}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is smooth,
 the following relation must hold:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\beta\left(\theta_{s}\right)\dot{\theta}_{s}^{2}+\gamma\left(\theta_{s}\right)=0,\label{eq:constr-for-dtheta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If this equation is solvable – that is,
 if coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(\theta_{s}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\left(\theta_{s}\right)$
\end_inset

 have opposite signs – then the mechanical system at the configuration 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{s}=\phi\left(\theta_{s}\right)$
\end_inset

 can move along the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'\left(\theta_{s}\right)$
\end_inset

,
 but only with a specific velocity given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{q}_{s}=\pm\sqrt{-\frac{\gamma\left(\theta_{s}\right)}{\beta\left(\theta_{s}\right)}}\phi'\left(\theta_{s}\right).
\]

\end_inset

A similar result is obtained when considering an implicit VHC 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(q_{*}\left(t\right)\right)\equiv0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case,
 the admissible velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{s}$
\end_inset

 can be determined by imposing the conditions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}h\left(q_{*}\left(t\right)\right)=0,\quad\frac{d^{2}}{dt^{2}}h\left(q_{*}\left(t\right)\right)=0\quad\text{at}\,t=t_{s}.
\]

\end_inset

These conditions lead to a system of two equations with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{s}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
NL_{\dot{q}_{s}}^{2}h\left(q_{s}\right)-Ndh\left(q_{s}\right)C\left(q_{s},\dot{q}_{s}\right)\dot{q}_{s} & =Ndh\left(q_{s}\right)G\left(q_{s}\right)\label{eq:condition-for-dq}\\
Ndh\left(q_{s}\right)\dot{q}_{s} & =0,\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\ker\left[dh\left(q_{s}\right)B\left(q_{s}\right)\right]^{\top}\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}_{s}=\dot{\theta}_{s}V$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $V\in\ker\left[Ndh\left(q_{s}\right)\right]\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a constant,
 treduces the system to a quadratic equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\theta}_{s}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N\left(L_{V}^{2}h\left(q_{s}\right)-dh\left(q_{s}\right)C\left(q_{s},V\right)V\right)\dot{\theta}_{s}^{2}=Ndh\left(q_{s}\right)G\left(q_{s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

which is equivalent to equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
